<p><b>General Assembly </b>Distr.: General 
19 May 2011 
English 
Original: Spanish </p>

<p><b>A/HRC/17/27/Add.3 
</b></p>
<p><b>2</b> GE.11-13248  (EXT) 
</p>
<p>determination of the causes and perpetrators of these crimes. Between 2000 and December 
2010 alone, 12 journalists were disappeared. The report also refers to recent attacks on 
media outlets. In some areas, journalists are subject to intimidation and self-censorship. 
The report finds that freedom of expression in Mexico faces serious obstacles. The figures 
mentioned have made Mexico the most dangerous country in the Americas in which to 
practise journalism. 
</p>
<p> In response to this grave situation, the report refers to the need to create a national 
mechanism for the protection of journalists. It argues that the new mechanism must be 
implemented through a high-level official inter-institutional committee, be headed by a 
federal authority, be able to coordinate among the various authorities and levels of 
government, have sufficient resources of its own and guarantee the participation of 
journalists and civil society organizations in its design, operation and evaluation. The 
Special Rapporteur recommends strengthening both the Special Prosecutor&#8217;s Office for 
Crimes against Freedom of Expression in the Attorney General&#8217;s Office and local 
prosecutor&#8217;s offices. 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p> The report notes that, in Mexico, ownership and control of media to which broadcast 
frequencies have been assigned are highly concentrated. There are no clear, precise and 
equitable procedures for awarding operating frequencies to community radio stations. The 
Special Rapporteur recommends the adoption of a regulatory framework that offers legal 
certainty, reduces the concentration of ownership and control of radio and television and 
helps generate pluralist media that are accessible to all sectors of the population. He 
expresses concern at the closure of some community radio stations on the basis of a 
regulatory framework that does not conform to international standards. 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p> The report notes that public spending on government advertising is high and 
increasing. There are cases where official advertising has been used as a means to pressure, 
reward, punish or favour media according to their editorial angle. Objective, clear, 
transparent and non-discriminatory criteria should be established for the allocation of 
official advertising at all levels and in all areas of government. 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p> The report makes a detailed analysis of criminal law and freedom of expression and 
of civil actions brought in connection with its exercise. The federal Government 
decriminalized slander, defamation and libel in 2007 and 18 states have followed suit. 
However, the 1917 Print Offences Act, which provides for custodial sentences, remains in 
force. The Attorney General&#8217;s Office has brought criminal proceedings against journalists 
working for community radio stations that did not have the necessary permits. The Special 
Rapporteur considers that journalists and media workers interested in public affairs, 
particularly those who investigate cases of corruption or wrongdoing, must not be subject 
to judicial or other harassment in retaliation for their work. Differentiated standards must 
be established for evaluating subsequent civil liability, including the standard of actual 
malice, as well as strict proportionality and reasonability of any subsequent penalties. 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p> 
